-- Hungarian court may rule on forex loans by mid-July - MTI
-- By Sandor Peto
-- Wed Apr 30, 2014 07:25AM EDT
-- None



BUDAPEST, April 30 (Reuters) - Hungary's top court may rule on a pivotal case affecting government plans to help foreign-currency borrowers before its July 15-Aug. 20 summer break rather than after it as previously expected, the national news agency reported on Wednesday.

The government is waiting for the court's ruling before it draws up legislation to ease the financial burden on people who took out loans in foreign currencies only to see their repayment costs soar as the forint slid <EURHUF=> in the wake of the 2008 global crisis.The national news agency, MTI, quoted an unnamed court press office source as saying the court will make its decision based on Wednesday's ruling issued by the European Court of Justice. [ID:nL6N0NM33W]